&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Green.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The first hour of every parliamentary sitting is slotted for the question hour.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;During this time, the members ask questions and the ministers usually give answers. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The questions are of three kinds:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ol style=&quot;margin-left: 40px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Starred:&amp;nbsp;A starred question (distinguished by an asterisk) requires an oral answer and hence supplementary questions can follow.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Unstarred:&amp;nbsp;An unstarred question requires a written answer and hence, supplementary questions cannot follow.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Short notice:&amp;nbsp;A short notice question is one that is asked by giving a notice of less than ten days. It is answered orally.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In addition to the ministers, the questions can also be asked to the private members.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, a question may be addressed to a private member if the subject matter of the question relates to some Bill, resolution, or other matter connected with the business of the House for which that member is responsible.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The procedure in regard to such a question is the same as that followed in the case of questions addressed to a minister.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The list of questions are printed in different colors as explained below: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ol style=&quot;margin-left: 40px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Starred: Green&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Unstarred: White&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Short notice questions: Light pink&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Questions to private members: Yellow&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Why the Question Hour is in the news:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Question Hour and Zero Hour are canceled for the upcoming Parliament session which will start on the 14th of September.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The opposition parties are opposing this move.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About the zero hour&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike the question hour, the zero hour is not mentioned in the Rules of Procedure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus it is an informal device available to the members of the Parliament to raise matters without any prior notice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The zero hour starts immediately after the question hour and lasts until the agenda for the day (i.e, regular business of the House) is taken up.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In other words, the time gap between the question hour and the agenda is known as zero hour.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is an Indian innovation in the field of parliamentary procedures and has been in existence since 1962.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Long wave terrestrial radiation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Terrestrial Radiation&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The insolation received by the earth is in the form of&amp;nbsp;shortwaves.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The earth after being heated itself becomes a radiating body and it&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;radiates energy to the atmosphere in the long waveform.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;This energy heats the atmosphere from below.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This process is known as&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;terrestrial radiation.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The longwave radiation is absorbed by atmospheric gases particularly by carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thus, the atmosphere is indirectly heated by the earth&amp;rsquo;s radiation.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The atmosphere in turn radiates and transmits heat to the space.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Finally, the amount of heat received from the sun is returned to space, thereby maintaining a constant temperature at the earth&amp;rsquo;s surface and in the atmosphere.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;earth does not heat up due to the short wave radiation&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;it gets from the sun.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Earth gets heated due to the greenhouse effect.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In the greenhouse effect,&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;greenhouse&amp;nbsp;gases absorb the terrestrial radiation and re-radiate the heat into the atmosphere thereby keeping it warm.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​Therefore, the atmosphere is mainly heated by long-wave terrestrial radiation. Hence, Option 3 is correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/11/6197409f184e305317508e0a_16378191928031.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 340px; width: 450px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The earth&amp;rsquo;s surface receives most of its energy in&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;short wavelengths.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The energy received by the earth is known as incoming solar radiation which in short is termed&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;insolation.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The atmosphere is largely&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;transparent to short-wave solar radiation.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The incoming solar radiation passes through the atmosphere before striking the earth&amp;rsquo;s surface.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In a federal set up there is a two-tier Government with well-assigned powers and functions.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this system, the central government and the governments of the units act within a well-defined sphere, coordinate and at the same time act independently.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The federal polity, in other words, provides a constitutional device for bringing unity in diversity and for the achievement of common national goals.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;55px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/images/production/quesImages/quesImage13.png&quot; width=&quot;180px&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Federal Features of the Indian Union:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Governments at two levels&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; centre and states&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Division of powers between the centre and states&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; there are three lists given in the&amp;nbsp;Seventh Schedule of the Constitution&amp;nbsp;which gives the subjects each level has jurisdiction in:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Union List&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;State List&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Concurrent List&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Supremacy of the constitution&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; the&amp;nbsp;basic structure of the constitution&amp;nbsp;is indestructible as laid out by the judiciary. The constitution is the supreme law in India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Independent judiciary&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; the constitution provides for an independent and integrated judiciary.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The lower and district courts are at the bottom levels, the high courts are at the state levels and at the topmost position is the&amp;nbsp;Supreme Court of India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;All courts are subordinate to the Supreme Court.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, we can conclude that the &lt;strong&gt;Supremacy of parliament is not a feature of the federal system&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dalton&amp;#39;s Law&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dalton&amp;#39;s Law:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Definition: &lt;/strong&gt;Dalton&amp;#39;s Law, also known as the Law of Partial Pressures, states that &lt;strong&gt;the total pressure exerted by a mixture of gases is the sum of the partial pressures of the individual gases.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Partial Pressure: &lt;/strong&gt;The pressure that each gas would exert if it alone occupied the entire volume of the mixture is its partial pressure.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Independent Behaviour: &lt;/strong&gt;The law assumes that gases behave independently of each other, meaning the pressure of each gas in a mixture is unaffected by the presence of other gases.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications: &lt;/strong&gt;Dalton&amp;#39;s Law has important applications in many areas including chemistry, physics, physiology, and even scuba diving, where understanding the pressures of different gas components is crucial.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;width: 350px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;thead&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;th&gt;Law&lt;/th&gt;
			&lt;th&gt;Description&lt;/th&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/thead&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Charles&amp;#39; Law&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;States that the volume of a given mass of an ideal gas is directly proportional to the absolute temperature provided its pressure remains constant.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Boyle&amp;#39;s Law&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Proposes an inverse relationship between the pressure and volume of a gas, assuming the temperature is kept constant within a closed system.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Graham&amp;#39;s Law&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Describes the relationship between the rates of diffusion of gases and their molar masses.&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;It states that the rate of diffusion of a gas is inversely proportional to the square root of its molar mass.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Parliament can constitute a high court for a union territory by law&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Parliament can also declare any court in any such territory to be a high court to the union territory&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Article 241 of the Indian Constitution addresses the High Courts for Union territory.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The said article is covered in Part VIII of the Constitution that deals with &amp;ldquo;The Union Territories&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

